\begin_layout Standard
In this paper,
 we test an alternative system that collects farmers’ evaluations of maize seed purchased from agro-dealers and aggregates them into ratings that summarize the experiences of multiple peers facing similar production conditions.
 These ratings are disseminated to both farmers and agro-dealers,
 providing a summary signal of seed performance at agro-dealers that individual farmers may find difficult to obtain through their own experimentation or social networks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rating system addresses key limitations of existing approaches.
 Ratings are disseminated directly to farmers,
 allowing information to reach those who do not typically visit agro-dealers.
 The system is decentralized and therefore relies less on institutional capacity.
 Importantly,
 it does not directly measure seed purity or certify authenticity.
 Instead,
 it reflects farmers’ evaluations of realized performance – whether the seed they purchased yielded well,
 germinated and matured reliably,
 and tolerated local conditions.
 While these assessments may diverge from laboratory measures of seed purity or authenticity,
 they capture performance dimensions that are directly relevant to farmers’ production decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aggregating and disseminating farmers’ purchasing experiences could improve outcomes through several channels.
 First,
 farmers may hold imprecise or biased beliefs about seed performance.
 Peer ratings could reduce uncertainty and increase confidence among all farmers and,
 when prior beliefs are pessimistic relative to the signal,
 raise expected seed performance among those without prior purchasing experience,
 thereby increasing adoption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second,
 agro-dealer-specific ratings could enable sorting by revealing relative performance differences across sellers,
 conditional on purchasing from agro-dealers.
 In agricultural input markets,
 farmers typically choose among a small number of local agro-dealers with limited information about relative seed performance.
 By aggregating dispersed information about seller-specific performance,
 ratings could support the kind of quality-based reallocation that characterizes markets with public seller feedback 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1086/688875,10.1257/aer.20161965"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 When ratings credibly reveal meaningful cross-dealer performance differences,
 and switching costs are not too high,
 farmers may reallocate purchases toward higher-performing sellers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third,
 the rating system could improve agro-dealer-level seed performance through supply-side accountability.
 In the prevailing market equilibrium,
 agro-dealers may have weak incentives to invest in seed storage and handling because farmers cannot credibly assess seed performance at the point of purchase and may struggle to attribute later outcomes such as germination or yield to agro-dealer behavior.
 By aggregating farmer experiences into visible ratings,
 the system creates bottom-up pressure on agro-dealers:
 poor seed performance becomes reputationally costly,
 while better-preserved seed can attract future demand.
 The rating system can therefore shift competition toward quality by making agro-dealer-level performance more observable to potential buyers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1162/003355303321675428,doi:10.1086/688875,hasanain2019no,doi:10.1086/734133"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These three channels are not mutually exclusive,
 but they generate distinct empirical predictions that allow us to assess their relative importance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We test this approach in a randomized controlled trial (RCT) involving approximately 3,500 smallholder farmers and 350 agro-dealers in the market for high-yielding maize seed in eastern Uganda.
 The randomized design allows us to estimate causal effects,
 while three rounds of detailed data enable us to understand how and why the intervention affects behavior.
 We track outcomes along the full causal chain,
 from farmers’ perceptions and adoption decisions to agricultural productivity and sales.
 Additional data on farmers’ choice of agro-dealers,
 agro-dealer seed handling practices,
 services,
 and signaling,
 and seed-performance indicators allow us to trace the channels through which the intervention operates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exposure to aggregated peer ratings increases adoption of high-yielding maize seed and purchases from agro-dealers,
 and treated farmers achieve yields on randomly selected maize plots that are 56 kg/acre higher than those of the control group at endline,
 equivalent to 13% of the baseline mean.
 The value of maize production net of seed costs is also 66,000 UGX higher for treated farmers.
 Because adoption and productivity effects are consistent with all three channels,
 interpretation rests on outcomes that are predicted to differ across pathways.
 The evidence points most strongly to belief updating:
 the intervention raises farmers’ perceptions of agro-dealer seed performance,
 while switching across agro-dealers increases modestly at midline but is not persistent.
 On the supply side,
 agro-dealers respond along service and signaling margins,
 but we do not detect improvements in seed handling,
 storage,
 or measured seed performance.
