\end_inset

 agro-dealers in farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

’s area,
 each with performance 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 This is the actual performance the farmer would realize if they planted the seed,
 unobservable at the time of purchase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}=\theta_{0}-d(e_{j})$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the intrinsic performance of the seed upon arrival at agro-dealer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

,
 determined upstream in the supply chain,
 outside the agro-dealer’s control,
 and assumed to be the same across agro-dealers,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This assumption abstracts from upstream variation in seed received by agro-dealers;
 allowing 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 to vary by agro-dealer would introduce an additional source of agro-dealer heterogeneity but would not affect the model’s distinction between belief updating,
 agro-dealer sorting,
 and supply-side accountability.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d(e_{j})\geq0$
\end_inset

 captures performance degradation due to handling and storage,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $d'(e_{j})<0$
\end_inset

.
 Higher agro-dealer effort 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{j}$
\end_inset

 (e.g.,
 proper storage containers,
 ventilation,
 temperature,
 and moisture control) reduces degradation,
 preserving seed performance closer to its intrinsic level 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because seed performance is unobservable at the time of purchase,
 the decision to buy seed depends on beliefs about the performance of agro-dealer seed relative to outside options 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}[\theta_{j}]$
\end_inset

.
 Seed has some properties of a credence good:
 because agricultural outcomes depend on many factors beyond the seed itself and individual learning is noisy,
 slow,
 and difficult to self-correct,
 farmers cannot fully assess seed performance even after use 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "AHMAD2022176,laajaj_macours_forthcoming"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is compounded by the disproportionate salience of negative information 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "neg_bias,vaish2008not,hornik2015information"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 which may push beliefs below the true 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Evidence from fertilizer markets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MICHELSON2021102579,https://doi.org/10.1111/ajae.12466"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and maize seed in Uganda 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BARRIGA2020104928"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is consistent with potentially downward-biased beliefs.
 At the same time,
 seed also has some properties of an experience good:
 farmers who have purchased and planted agro-dealer seed can form more accurate beliefs than those who have not 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "foster1995learning"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmers are risk-averse and face a two-part decision:
 whether to purchase seed from any agro-dealer rather than rely on an outside option (extensive margin),
 and if so,
 from which agro-dealer (agro-dealer choice).
 Farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 evaluates each agro-dealer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 by comparing the expected performance of that agro-dealer’s seed,
 discounted for uncertainty,
 against the purchase cost.
 Formally,
 the farmer purchases from the best available agro-dealer if the certainty equivalent exceeds the cost:
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RESOLVED:
 Yes,
 max_j selects the best available agro-dealer.
 The max operates over the entire certainty-equivalent expression (E[θ] minus risk penalty minus cost),
 not just the expectation.
 So it reads:
 "the farmer buys from whichever agro-dealer j gives the highest certainty equivalent,
 provided that exceeds zero (the outside option)." This is standard notation in discrete choice models.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{j}\;E_{i}[\theta_{j}]-\frac{\rho}{2}\sigma^{2}_{ij}-c_{j}>0\label{eq:adoption_main}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

’s subjective uncertainty about agro-dealer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

’s seed performance,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho>0$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient of absolute risk aversion,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}>0$
\end_inset

 is the cost of purchasing from agro-dealer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 relative to the outside option.
 Adoption depends on both expected performance and subjective performance uncertainty:
 even at the same expected return,
 greater uncertainty discourages adoption.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RESOLVED:
 Moot —
 the "Seed purchasing under uncertainty" subsection was merged into Setup.
 "Adoption" is the correct and consistent term throughout the paper.
\end_layout

