\begin_layout Subsection
Belief updating
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Belief updating"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 does not observe 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

;
 instead,
 they hold a prior belief 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{ij}\equiv E_{i}[\theta_{j}]$
\end_inset

 about agro-dealer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

’s seed performance:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}\mid\mathcal{I}_{i}\sim\mathcal{N}(\mu_{ij},\sigma^{2}_{ij})$
\end_inset

.
 Priors are likely to be imprecise or biased.
 The intervention can affect outcomes by shaping belief formation about 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 In our model,
 the way it does so depends on farmers’ prior seed purchasing experience from agro-dealers,
 generating predictions about heterogeneous treatment effects.
 In particular,
 we distinguish two types:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Purchasers
\series default
 (
\begin_inset Formula $i\in P$
\end_inset

) have prior beliefs informed by their own purchasing experience;
 as a result,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{Pj}$
\end_inset

 is close to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Non-purchasers
\series default
 (
\begin_inset Formula $i\in NP$
\end_inset

) lack own purchasing experience:
 we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{NPj}>\sigma^{2}_{Pj}$
\end_inset

 (greater uncertainty),
 and allow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{NPj}$
\end_inset

 to differ from 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Farmers without experience hold more biased and less precise priors.
 In the empirically relevant case of pessimistic priors,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{NPj}<\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intervention provides farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 with a signal about the performance of seed from agro-dealer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 The signal aggregates the experiences of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{j}$
\end_inset

 farmers who purchased from agro-dealer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{j}=\frac{1}{n_{j}}\sum^{n_{j}}_{k=1}(\theta_{j}+\varepsilon_{k})=\bar{\theta}_{j}+\bar{\varepsilon}_{j}\label{eq:signal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the noise in rater 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

’s (drawn from the pool of previous purchasers) individual experience (reflecting weather,
 soil,
 management,
 and other factors beyond seed performance) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varepsilon}_{j}\sim\mathcal{N}(0,\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}/n_{j})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To characterize how such a signal changes beliefs,
 we use the standard conjugate Normal-Normal Bayesian updating framework.
 Given farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

’s prior belief about agro-dealer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

’s seed performance 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and the signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{j}$
\end_inset

,
 posterior mean and variance are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\mu}_{ij}=(1-\alpha_{ij})\mu_{ij}+\alpha_{ij}s_{j},\quad\tilde{\sigma}^{2}_{ij}=\frac{\sigma^{2}_{ij}\cdot\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}/n_{j}}{\sigma^{2}_{ij}+\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}/n_{j}}\label{eq:updating_main}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with the weight on the signal,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ij}=\frac{\sigma^{2}_{ij}}{\sigma^{2}_{ij}+\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}/n_{j}}$
\end_inset

,
 increasing in prior subjective uncertainty 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Bayesian updating expression should be interpreted as a benchmark in which farmers perceive the rating signal as credible and relevant.
 Lower credibility or attention would attenuate the weight placed on 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{j}$
\end_inset

,
 without altering the model’s qualitative predictions.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{NPj}>\sigma^{2}_{Pj}$
\end_inset

,
 non-purchasers place more weight on the signal and experience larger reductions in posterior uncertainty.
 The belief shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mu}_{ij}-\mu_{ij}=\alpha_{ij}(s_{j}-\mu_{ij})$
\end_inset

 is positive when the signal is more favorable than the prior.
 For purchasers,
 the main effect is a precision gain (lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\sigma}^{2}_{ij}$
\end_inset

);
 for non-purchasers,
 the model predicts a larger precision gain and,
 when priors are pessimistic relative to the signal,
 a larger upward revision in expected performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{j}$
\end_inset

 as an informative peer-experience signal rather than an unbiased estimate of agro-dealer-specific performance,
 since it need not represent the experience that any farmer would have with agro-dealer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Raters are drawn from previous purchasers and may differ from non-purchasers along dimensions beyond prior beliefs,
 but the model requires that average rater experiences contain information about agro-dealer seed performance beyond selection-driven differences across farmers.
 Under this condition,
 averaging across raters reduces idiosyncratic noise:
 more raters generate a more precise signal about agro-dealer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

’s seed performance.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

