\begin_layout Subsection
Agro-dealer sorting
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Dealer-sorting"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the belief-updating channel captures changes in farmers’ beliefs about agro-dealer seed relative to outside options,
 agro-dealer sorting captures changes in seller choice conditional on purchasing from an agro-dealer.
 Because the intervention provides agro-dealer-specific ratings (
\begin_inset Formula $s_{j}$
\end_inset

),
 it conveys two types of information.
 First,
 the average signal across agro-dealers,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{s}=\frac{1}{J}\sum_{j}s_{j}$
\end_inset

,
 provides information about overall seed performance,
 allowing farmers to update beliefs about agro-dealers as a group.
 Second,
 differences in signals across agro-dealers and deviations from the average,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{j}-\bar{s}$
\end_inset

,
 reveal performance differences and enable sorting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whether sorting occurs depends on the dispersion in 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

 across agro-dealers.
 If performance varies substantially across agro-dealers and ratings reveal this,
 farmers can switch to higher-rated agro-dealers.
 If ratings are similar across agro-dealers,
 the signal contains little agro-dealer-specific information,
 weakening the sorting channel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Supply-side accountability
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Supply-side accountability"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intervention can also induce agro-dealers to reduce degradation 
\begin_inset Formula $d(e_{j})$
\end_inset

,
 thereby increasing performance 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

 itself.
 This operates through a supply-side accountability channel:
 by aggregating farmers’ experiences into an observable signal,
 the intervention raises the reputational cost of exerting low effort and selling poorly preserved seed.
 Once ratings are disseminated to farmers,
 agro-dealers’ performance becomes visible to potential buyers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{j}\geq0$
\end_inset

 denote agro-dealer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

’s effort in seed preservation (e.g.,
 proper storage containers,
 ventilation,
 temperature,
 and moisture control),
 with convex cost 
\begin_inset Formula $c(e_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}=\theta_{0}-d(e_{j})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $d’(e_{j})<0$
\end_inset

:
 higher effort in seed storage and handling reduces degradation,
 preserving seed performance closer to its intrinsic level 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Without the intervention,
 agro-dealers’ reputational incentives are limited to repeat purchases and informal word of mouth.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{C}(\theta_{j})$
\end_inset

 denote demand for agro-dealer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in the absence of the intervention,
 that depends on quality through these informal channels,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{C}’>0$
\end_inset

.
 Under the intervention,
 ratings are collected and disseminated,
 strengthening the reputational return to quality.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{T}(\theta_{j})$
\end_inset

 denote demand under the rating system,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{T}’(\theta_{j})>R_{C}’(\theta_{j})$
\end_inset

:
 the marginal return to quality is higher when performance is publicly visible.
 The agro-dealer chooses effort to maximize:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{e_{j}}\quad R_{\tau}(\theta_{0}-d(e_{j}))-c(e_{j}),\quad\tau\in\{C,T\}\label{eq:dealer_main}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first-order condition is 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\tau}’(\theta_{0}-d(e^{*}_{j}))(-d’(e^{*}_{j}))=c’(e^{*}_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{T}’>R_{C}’$
\end_inset

,
 the optimal effort is higher under the intervention:
 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{*}_{jT}>e^{*}_{jC}$
\end_inset

.
 If agro-dealers respond to the intervention by investing in seed preservation,
 degradation falls and performance improves.
 If the belief-updating and supply-side accountability channels operate simultaneously,
 they may reinforce each other:
 updated beliefs increase farmers’ willingness to engage with agro-dealers,
 while better seed preservation strengthens the actual purchasing experience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Testable predictions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model identifies three channels through which the intervention may affect outcomes:
 belief updating (Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Belief updating"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

),
 agro-dealer sorting (Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Dealer-sorting"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

),
 and supply-side accountability (Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Supply-side accountability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

).
 Each channel generates distinct predictions across five outcomes,
 summarized in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:predictions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Prediction 1 (Perceptions).

\series default
 Under the belief-updating channel,
 the treatment shifts perceived seed performance in the direction of the signal,
 with stronger effects among non-purchasers.
 If priors are pessimistic relative to the signal,
 perceptions shift upward.
 Under the agro-dealer sorting channel,
 there may be an indirect effect on perceptions if farmers sort to higher-rated agro-dealers and subsequently experience better seed performance.
 Under the supply-side accountability channel,
 perceptions may also improve indirectly if agro-dealers adjust their effort and improved objective seed performance becomes visible.
 For both channels,
 effects need not be concentrated among non-purchasers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Prediction 2 (Adoption).

\series default
 Under the belief-updating channel,
 the treatment increases adoption by reducing uncertainty and,
 if priors are pessimistic relative to the signal,
 by raising expected performance above the adoption threshold.
 Under the agro-dealer sorting and supply-side accountability channels,
 the treatment may increase adoption through indirect effects on farmers’ perceptions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Prediction 3 (Productivity).

\series default
 All three channels can increase yields if they increase adoption of genuinely higher-performing seed relative to outside options.
 Agro-dealer sorting and supply-side accountability may additionally increase yields conditional on adoption – through sorting toward better agro-dealers and through improving objective seed performance,
 respectively – thereby enhancing the performance of seed actually purchased and planted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Prediction 4 (Switching).

\series default
 Under the belief-updating channel,
 the treatment does not reallocate farmers across agro-dealers.
 Under the agro-dealer sorting channel,
 the treatment increases switching toward higher-rated agro-dealers,
 as agro-dealer-specific ratings reveal performance differences.
 Absence of persistent increases in switching,
 or switching not directed toward higher-rated agro-dealers,
 weakens the evidence for agro-dealer sorting as the primary channel.
 Under the supply-side accountability channel,
 the treatment does not affect switching.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Prediction 5 (Seed performance).

\series default
 Under the belief-updating channel,
 the treatment shifts perceived but not objective seed performance at a given agro-dealer.
 Under the agro-dealer sorting channel,
 the treatment changes the performance of seed actually purchased at the farmer level when farmers switch toward better agro-dealers,
 but this does not operate through product improvement at the agro-dealer level.
 Under the supply-side accountability channel,
 seed degradation falls and performance improves as agro-dealers respond to reputational incentives by increasing effort in seed preservation.
 Finding no treatment effect on agro-dealer-level seed performance weakens the evidence for the supply-side accountability channel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The channels may also differ in their predicted timing of effects.
 Belief updating may shift perceptions as soon as farmers receive ratings,
 with effects on adoption materializing at the next purchase occasion.
 Agro-dealer sorting may induce switching at the next purchase occasion,
 while effects on perceptions and adoption may materialize later,
 when farmers experience better seed performance at higher-rated agro-dealers.
 Supply-side accountability may first induce agro-dealer improvements in seed storage and handling,
 which then translate into improved seed performance and subsequently become observable to farmers through experience or updated ratings;
 effects on perceptions and adoption may therefore take longer to materialize.
 This timing distinction is useful for interpreting whether effects appear at midline,
 persist through endline,
 or emerge only after an additional rating cycle.
\end_layout

