\begin_layout Subsection
Rating data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At endline,
 the rating intervention generated a dyadic dataset comprising of 16,823 farmer-dealer links.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In 61% of cases,
 farmers reported knowing the dealer they were asked to rate.
 Among those who knew the dealer,
 21% had personally purchased seed there.
 Among those without direct purchase experience,
 2% reported knowing someone who had purchased seed from that dealer.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Among farmers who provided at least one rating,
 the average farmer rated 1.4 agro-dealers (min = 1,
 max = 10).
 The average agro-dealer was rated by 6.7 farmers (min = 0,
 max = 30).
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Restricting to agro-dealers who received at least one rating,
 the average number of farmers per dealer is 7.085 (min = 1,
 max = 30).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because ratings could be provided either by farmers who had personally purchased seed from the agro-dealer or by those who knew someone who had,
 the signal may reflect indirect information rather than firsthand performance experience.
 In practice,
 93% of ratings were provided by farmers with direct purchase experience,
 and ratings are similar between purchasers and non-purchasers (see Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.4 Agro-dealer rating patterns"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for details).
 This suggests that the aggregate signal predominantly reflects direct experience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ratings may also reflect factors unrelated to seed performance,
 such as customer service or personal relationships.
 Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.4 Agro-dealer rating patterns"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 provides suggestive evidence that ratings are associated with observable characteristics plausibly related to seller and seed performance:
 specialized agro-shops and dealers with better seed handling practices receive higher ratings,
 and seed ratings on randomly selected fields are positively correlated with maize yields.
 These patterns are consistent with ratings reflecting farmers’ assessments of seed performance rather than purely non-performance attributes.
 Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.4 Agro-dealer rating patterns"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 provides additional detail on the rating data,
 including the distribution of ratings across the six performance dimensions and their inter-correlations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "6 Results"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We report treatment effects for both farmers and agro-dealers at midline (after one agricultural season) and at endline (after two seasons).
 All outcome variables were pre-specified in a pre-analysis plan at the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "AEA's registry for RCTs"
target "https://www.socialscienceregistry.org/trials/6361"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The econometric analysis was run on simulated data prior to outcome data collection and documented in a 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "registered report"
target "https://github.com/bjvca/Seed_systems_project/tree/master/papers/mock_report"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "humphreys2013fishing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 All documents,
 code,
 and data are publicly available in a version-controlled 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "GitHub repository"
target "https://github.com/bjvca/Seed_systems_project"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The presentation of results differs slightly from the pre-registered structure due to a reordering of outcomes,
 which modifies the construction of some pre-specified indices but leaves the main conclusions unchanged.
 Analyses adhering strictly to the pre-analysis plan remain publicly available in the project repository (see,
 e.g.,
 the archived version linked 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "https://github.com/bjvca/Seed_systems_project/blob/96170af9ac893eabbde0785016a990a26707652c/papers/clearinghouse_training_paper/clearinghouse_training_paper.pdf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our primary approach to interpreting mechanisms relies on the pattern of effects across outcomes:
 each channel generates a distinct empirical signature across perceptions,
 adoption,
 productivity,
 switching,
 and seed performance (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:predictions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 We also examine heterogeneity by prior seed purchasing experience.
 Although this analysis was not pre-specified and is therefore exploratory,
 it is motivated by the model’s prediction that farmers with greater uncertainty about seed performance should place more weight on the signal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Perceived seed performance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by testing whether the treatment shifts farmers’ perceptions of maize seed performance at agro-dealers.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects of clearinghouse on farmer perceptions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports treatment effects on a perception index combining farmer ratings across six dimensions:
 general quality,
 yield,
 drought tolerance,
 pest and disease tolerance,
 maturity time,
 and germination.
 The treatment increases this index by 0.09 standard deviations,
 significant at the 10% level.
 The positive effect is consistent with the belief-updating channel if the peer signal is more favorable than farmers’ prior beliefs about agro-dealer seed performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These estimates should be interpreted with caution.
 Ratings were collected from control farmers only at endline,
 and the perception index requires non-missing ratings on all six dimensions for at least one agro-dealer.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A total of 1,534 farmers purchased seed from an agro-input shop for at least one plot at endline,
 so it is unsurprising to observe 1,664 farmers with non-missing ratings on all six dimensions for at least one agro-dealer.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As a result,
 treatment effects on perceptions are estimated only for the final survey round and less precisely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model also predicts stronger updating among farmers with greater prior uncertainty.
 We examine this using prior agro-dealer seed-purchasing experience,
 proxied by whether the farmer used maize seed from an agro-dealer in the season preceding baseline.
 The subgroup estimates are similar:
 0.10 standard deviations among farmers without prior experience,
 compared to 0.09 in the full sample,
 and a formal interaction test does not reject equality.
 We therefore interpret the perception results as evidence of upward belief updating overall,
 rather than differential updating by prior experience.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Importantly,
 the farmers who provided ratings – primarily those with firsthand purchasing experience – differ from those who received them,
 which include both purchasers and non-purchasers.
 This asymmetry increases the likelihood that the information encountered diverged from prior beliefs.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

