\begin_layout Standard
We then assess whether the shift toward agro-dealer seed at the farmer level is reflected in agro-dealer business activity (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects on dealer outcomes at end of causal chain: Business volume"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

).
 Outcomes include sales volume for the four most commonly purchased maize varieties (Longe 7H,
 Longe 10H,
 Longe 4,
 and Longe 5),
 average prices,
 implied revenue,
 the number of maize-seed customers served per day,
 and the number of maize varieties stocked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The agro-dealer results are consistent with increased engagement at the farmer level.
 At midline,
 treated agro-dealers score significantly higher on the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "anderson2008multiple"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 index,
 and their revenue is nearly 20% higher than that of control agro-dealers,
 significant at the 10% level.
 This revenue effect appears more consistent with higher sales volumes (28.4% relative to baseline) than with higher prices (2.3% relative to baseline),
 although neither component is individually statistically significant.
 At endline,
 the treatment effect on the business-activity index is significant at the 1% level,
 driven primarily by treated agro-dealers reporting 31% more customers than control agro-dealers,
 equivalent to roughly six additional customers per day.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Agro-dealers could display the certificate in their shops,
 and at endline it was visible in 56% of them.
 Ratings may therefore have been observed by non-sampled farmers,
 extending exposure beyond the study sample.
 Because randomization occurred at the catchment-area level,
 any such additional exposure remains within treated areas and does not threaten identification.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.5 Treatment effects on agro-dealer operations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports business outcomes for two recently released maize varieties (Longe 10H and Longe 5),
 further supporting this pattern.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taken together,
 the farmer and agro-dealer results show that the intervention shifts farmers toward purchasing seed from agro-dealers.
 These effects are consistent with the model’s adoption prediction,
 but because all three channels can affect sourcing decisions,
 they do not identify a specific mechanism.
\end_layout

