\begin_layout Subsection

\series bold
Productivity
\series default
 and harvest outcomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We examine harvest-related outcomes on a randomly selected maize plot in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects on farmer outcomes at end of causal chain: Harvest"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 These include production,
 plot size,
 yield,
 the value of maize production at market prices net of seed costs,
 maize retained for seed in the following season,
 and maize sales outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The overall index shows a positive and statistically significant treatment effect at endline.
 Treated farmers achieve yields that are 56 kilograms per acre higher than those of control farmers,
 a 13% increase relative to the baseline mean and significant at the 1% level.
 The value of maize production net of seed costs is 66,000 UGX higher for treated farmers,
 approximately 18 USD at the time of the survey.
 Treated farmers also retain less maize for seed at midline,
 consistent with reduced reliance on farmer-saved seed.
 We find no effects on the quantity of maize sold or on revenue,
 suggesting that the yield gains do not translate into larger marketed surpluses and that additional output remains within the household.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These harvest effects provide evidence that the intervention improves realized agricultural outcomes beyond beliefs and sourcing decisions.
 They are consistent with the model’s prediction that credible seed-performance information increases productivity by shifting farmers toward higher-performing seed or by improving the performance of the seed they actually purchase.
 However,
 the observed yield gains are consistent with all three channels – belief updating,
 agro-dealer sorting,
 and supply-side accountability – and therefore do not by themselves identify a specific mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A back-of-the-envelope calculation suggests that increased adoption alone is unlikely to fully explain the observed yield effect.
 Even if improved varieties yield 72% more than farmer-saved seed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "JOVANOVIC2025103466"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 the approximately five percentage point increase in agro-dealer sourcing would account for only a modest share of the observed 56 kg/acre yield gain.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
At midline,
 778 treated farmers (44%) and 567 control farmers (40%) bought seed at agro-input shop for specific plot,
 and 985 and 860 did not.
 The average midline yield is 335.419 kg/acre.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
((778*X*335.419)+(985*1*335.419))/(778+985)-((567*X*335.419)+(860*1*335.419))/(567+860)=49.552
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
X=4.3604
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remaining effect likely reflects changes in how farmers use purchased seed.
 By reducing uncertainty about seed performance,
 the intervention may encourage greater investment in complementary inputs whose returns depend on seed quality,
 as documented by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.1257/aer.20150474"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Consistent with this,
 treated farmers are about 5 percentage points more likely to use inorganic fertilizer at both midline and endline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A related explanation is the reallocation of labor.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bulte2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that greater certainty about seed quality raises yields and reduces crop failure by inducing farmers to invest more effort.
 We find suggestive evidence consistent with this at midline:
 treated farmers are less likely to intercrop and more likely to plant the recommended number of seeds per hill,
 both indicative of increased production effort.
\end_layout

