\begin_layout Standard
We then examine whether these agro-dealer responses translate into measurable improvements in seed performance.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects on bag of maize seed bought at dealer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports treatment effects on several seed-performance indicators.
 Enumerators purchased an original,
 sealed bag of maize seed from agro-dealers and assessed moisture content,
 packaging integrity,
 and packaging information.
 Consistent with the absence of changes in seed handling and storage practices most directly related to seed preservation,
 we find no significant treatment effects on any of these indicators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because not all sampled agro-dealers had maize seed in stock at the time of the survey,
 the seed-performance sample is smaller than the main sample.
 To assess whether the null result reflects limited statistical precision,
 Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.9 Treatment effects on agro-dealers’ seed PERFORMANCE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports a power analysis for moisture content,
 a pre-registered objective indicator of seed performance.
 The analysis shows that the estimated endline effect is small relative to the variation in the data and would remain difficult to detect even with a substantially larger sample.
 As a complementary check,
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects on dealer memberships. licenses. inspections"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

 examines additional seed-performance proxies available for larger samples and again finds no treatment effects.
 We therefore find no evidence of detectable improvements in the measured seed-performance indicators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taken together,
 the supply-side results provide some evidence that agro-dealers respond to the intervention,
 primarily along service and signaling margins.
 However,
 we find no detectable improvements in seed handling,
 storage,
 or measured seed performance.
 The evidence therefore points to a limited supply-side response,
 but provides no support for supply-side accountability as the primary channel,
 which would require reputational pressure to translate into improvements in the objective performance of seed sold by agro-dealers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and may not fully capture the seed available to farmers at planting.
 In particular,
 if higher-performing agro-dealers sold out earlier,
 or if the relevant quality margin occurred for seed purchased earlier in the season,
 bag-level measures collected at survey time could understate supply-side improvements.
\end_layout

